Here's an example of how you could implement a middleware-based approach to authorization in your ASP.NET Core application:

1. Define an authorization policy

In your `Startup.cs` file, define an authorization policy that combines the necessary rights and constraints for a particular operation. For example, you could define a policy named `ApprovePurchaseOrder` that requires the `ApprovePurchaseOrder` right with the appropriate country and customer level constraints:
```csharp
services.AddAuthorization(options =>
{
    options.AddPolicy("ApprovePurchaseOrder", policy =>
    {
        policy.RequireClaim("rights", "ApprovePurchaseOrder");
        policy.RequireClaim("country", "Norway");
        policy.RequireClaim("customerLevel", "gold", "platinum");
    });
});
```
2. Define a middleware component

Define a middleware component that checks if the user is authorized to access the requested resource. You could define this middleware as a separate class in your application:
```csharp
public class AuthorizationMiddleware
{
    private readonly RequestDelegate _next;

    public AuthorizationMiddleware(RequestDelegate next)
    {
        _next = next;
    }

    public async Task Invoke(HttpContext context, IAuthorizationService authorizationService)
    {
        // Check if the user is authorized to access the requested resource
        var authResult = await authorizationService.AuthorizeAsync(context.User, null, "ApprovePurchaseOrder");

        if (!authResult.Succeeded)
        {
            // User is not authorized, return a 403 Forbidden response
            context.Response.StatusCode = 403;
            await context.Response.WriteAsync("You are not authorized to access this resource.");
            return;
        }

        // User is authorized, continue with the next middleware component
        await _next(context);
    }
}
```
In this middleware component, we use the `IAuthorizationService` to check if the user is authorized to access the requested resource. We pass in the current user, a null resource, and the name of the `ApprovePurchaseOrder` policy. If the authorization check fails, we return a 403 Forbidden response. If the authorization check succeeds, we continue with the next middleware component in the pipeline.

3. Add the middleware to the pipeline

Add the `AuthorizationMiddleware` to the middleware pipeline in your `Startup.cs` file, after the authentication middleware:
```csharp
app.UseAuthentication();

app.UseMiddleware<AuthorizationMiddleware>();

app.UseMvc();
```
In this example, we assume that you have added authentication middleware to your pipeline using `app.UseAuthentication()`. We then add the `AuthorizationMiddleware` to the pipeline, and finally use the MVC middleware to handle the incoming requests.

This middleware-based approach to authorization has several advantages over the previous approach. It allows you to define authorization policies in a more modular and declarative way, and makes the code more reusable and easier to maintain.

To define authorization policies centrally and evaluate them using a rego rule, you could use the Open Policy Agent (OPA) as the policy engine for your application. Here's an example of how you could do this:

1. Define authorization policies in OPA

In OPA, define your authorization policies as rego rules. For example, you could define a rule that checks if the user has the `ApprovePurchaseOrder` right with the appropriate country and customer level constraints:
```rego
package myapp.authz

approve_purchase_order {
    input.rights[_] == "ApprovePurchaseOrder"
    input.constraints.country == "Norway"
    input.constraints.customerLevel[_] == "gold"
    input.constraints.customerLevel[_] == "platinum"
}
```
In this example, the `approve_purchase_order` rule checks if the user has the `ApprovePurchaseOrder` right with the appropriate country and customer level constraints. The rule uses the `input` variable to access the JSON data of the user's rights and constraints.

2. Configure OPA to act as a policy engine for your application

In your C# application, configure OPA to act as a policy engine for your authorization system. You can use the `OPA.NET` library to integrate OPA with your application.
```csharp
services.AddAuthorization(options =>
{
    options.AddPolicy("ApprovePurchaseOrder", policy =>
    {
        policy.Requirements.Add(new OpaAuthorizationRequirement("approve_purchase_order"));
    });
});

services.AddSingleton<IOpaHttpClientFactory, OpaHttpClientFactory>();

services.AddHttpClient<IOpaHttpClient, OpaHttpClient>()
        .ConfigureHttpClient((services, client) =>
        {
            var opaOptions = services.GetRequiredService<IOptions<OpaOptions>>().Value;

            client.BaseAddress = opaOptions.Url;
        });

services.AddOpaAuthorization(options =>
{
    options.Url = new Uri(Configuration["Opa:Url"]);
});
```
In this example, we add an authorization policy named `ApprovePurchaseOrder` that requires the `approve_purchase_order` rule defined in OPA. We use the `OpaAuthorizationRequirement` class to define the requirement, which takes the name of the OPA rule as an argument.

We also configure the `OpaHttpClientFactory` and `OpaHttpClient` to connect to the OPA server using the `OpaOptions` configuration settings. We then add the `AddOpaAuthorization` extension method to the `IServiceCollection` to register the OPA authorization services.

3. Evaluate authorization policies using OPA

In your authorization middleware component, evaluate the authorization policies using OPA. You can use the `IOpaAuthorizationService` to evaluate the policies.
```csharp
public class AuthorizationMiddleware
{
    private readonly RequestDelegate _next;

    public AuthorizationMiddleware(RequestDelegate next)
    {
        _next = next;
    }

    public async Task Invoke(HttpContext context, IOpaAuthorizationService authorizationService)
    {
        // Evaluate the authorization policy using OPA
        var authResult = await authorizationService.AuthorizeAsync(context.User, "ApprovePurchaseOrder");

        if (!authResult.Succeeded)
        {
            // User is not authorized, return a 403 Forbidden response
            context.Response.StatusCode = 403;
            await context.Response.WriteAsync("You are not authorized to access this resource.");
            return;
        }

        // User is authorized, continue with the next middleware component
        await _next(context);
    }
}
```
In this example, we use the `IOpaAuthorizationService` to evaluate the `ApprovePurchaseOrder` policy. We pass in the current user and the name of the policy to evaluate. If the authorization check fails, we return a 403 Forbidden response.

To make your rego rules less hard coded and authorize access based on the user's rights and constraints, you can pass the user's rights and constraints as input to the rego rule. Here's an example:

1. Define your authorization policy as a rego rule
```rego
package myapp.authz

has_right_with_constraints[right] {
    # Check if the user has the right
    input.rights[_] == right

    # Check if the user meets all of the constraints for the right
    all(constraint in input.constraints[_]) {
        constraint_matches(constraint)
    }
}

constraint_matches(constraint) {
    # Check if the constraint is specified in the right's definition
    definition := data.rights[constraint.name]
    definition

    # Check if the constraint's value matches the value in the user's constraints
    definition[constraint.name] == constraint.value
}
```
In this example, the `has_right_with_constraints` rule checks if the user has the specified right with the appropriate constraints. The `input` variable is used to access the JSON data of the user's rights and constraints.

The `constraint_matches` function checks if a single constraint matches the right's definition.

2. Pass the user's rights and constraints as input to the rego rule

In your C# application, pass the user's rights and constraints as input to the `OPA.NET` library when evaluating the authorization policies.
```csharp
var rights = new[] { "ApprovePurchaseOrder", "CreatePurchaseOrder" };
var constraints = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "country", "Norway" },
    { "customerLevel", new[] { "gold", "platinum" } }
};

var input = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "rights", rights },
    { "constraints", constraints }
};

var authzService = serviceProvider.GetRequiredService<IOpaAuthorizationService>();

var result = await authzService.AuthorizeAsync(user, input, "myapp.authz.has_right_with_constraints");
```
In this example, we pass the user's rights and constraints as input to the `AuthorizeAsync` method of the `IOpaAuthorizationService`. The `AuthorizeAsync` method also takes the name of the rego rule to evaluate as an argument.

The `result` variable contains the result of the authorization check. If the user is authorized, the `result.IsAuthorized` property will be `true`. If the user is not authorized, the `result.IsAuthorized` property will be `false`.
